## 4. Problem Formulation

Langford, BC, despite its rapid demographic and economic expansion, lacks an open-access community facility for residents to develop practical STEM skills using professional-grade equipment without post-secondary enrollment. Existing alternatives either restrict access to enrolled students or impose application-based membership barriers unsuited to beginners. Consequently, career changers, youth exploring STEM interests, and local professionals lack affordable, structured access to hands-on technical education.

### 4.1 Competitive Landscape

A direct comparison of existing facilities in the Greater Victoria region demonstrates the access gap Crossroads is designed to fill:

| Facility | Access Model | Approx. Cost | Hours | Equipment Scope | Target Audience |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| University of Victoria (~22,000 students) | Restricted to enrolled students | Tuition-based | Institutional hours only | Full STEM labs | Enrolled students |
| Camosun College (~19,000 learners) | Restricted to enrolled students | Tuition-based | Institutional hours only | Full STEM labs, CTAC | Enrolled students |
| Victoria Makerspace | Application-based membership | Membership fee | Limited public hours | Narrow hobbyist range | Hobbyists, makers |
| **Crossroads (Proposed)** | **Open-access, drop-in** | **$60/mo or $15 drop-in** | **73 hrs/week** | **4-discipline professional labs** | **All community members** |

Community feedback on public forums identifies Victoria Makerspace barriers for beginners and a lack of structured programming. Neither UVic nor Camosun provide community access outside of enrollment. Crossroads is positioned as the first facility in the West Shore offering structured, hands-on STEM access without enrollment or application barriers.

### 4.2 Demand Quantification

The February 2026 community needs assessment survey (n=54) quantifies demand across four discipline areas:

- **3D Printing / Digital Fabrication:** 72% interest
- **Software Development:** 58% interest
- **Robotics / Electronics:** 54% interest
- **Creative and Applied Design:** 41% interest

Additionally, 68% of respondents preferred weekday evening access and 59% preferred weekend availability, both of which are accommodated by the proposed 73-hour weekly schedule.

