## 6. Determination of Viability

### 6.1 Technical Feasibility

The required equipment is commercially available and well-documented. The facility requires 200-amp electrical service, industrial ventilation for fabrication areas, and compliance with the Accessible Canada Act. These requirements are standard for light industrial spaces available in Langford's McCallum Road and West Shore Parkway zones.

#### 6.1.1 Equipment Inventory (Lean Model)

The following equipment has been specified for the Lean Model launch, organized by discipline:

**Robotics and Electronics:**
- 20x Arduino Uno R4 starter kits
- 10x Raspberry Pi 5 kits
- 6x soldering stations (with fume extraction)
- 4x benchtop oscilloscopes
- Component inventory and test benches

**Digital Fabrication:**
- 2-4x FDM 3D printers
- 1x 40W CO2 laser cutter (enclosed with safety interlock)
- 1x benchtop CNC router (with dust collection)

**Software Development and Creative Design:**
- 10-15x computing workstations
- 6x drawing tablets
- Design software licenses (CAD, illustration, development environments)
- Networking equipment

Surplus equipment from post-secondary institutions (notably Camosun College CTAC) is projected to offset $15,000 to $30,000 of startup equipment costs under the Lean Model.

#### 6.1.2 Facility Requirements

- **Electrical:** 200-amp service with dedicated circuits for high-draw equipment (laser cutter, CNC router, multiple workstations)
- **Ventilation:** Industrial ventilation for fabrication areas, soldering fume extraction, dust collection system for CNC operations
- **ESD Protection:** ESD-safe workstations in the electronics area
- **Accessibility:** Full compliance with the Accessible Canada Act
- **Data Protection:** UPS battery backup for computing workstations

Suitable light industrial spaces are available in Langford at current lease rates of $16-$22/sqft net plus $6-$9/sqft NNN.

#### 6.1.3 Safety Protocols

All new participants must complete a mandatory 30-minute safety orientation, offered free of charge. The orientation covers facility rules, emergency procedures, and equipment-specific hazards per WorkSafeBC guidelines. Upon completion, participants receive immediate drop-in access.

**Hazard Classes by Discipline:**

- **Robotics and Electronics:** Soldering ventilation, ESD-safe workstations, battery fire-safe storage, eye protection for component work.
- **Digital Fabrication:** Machine guarding on CNC router, dust collection system, laser safety enclosure, face shields for material cutting operations.
- **Software Development:** Standard workstation ergonomics; no high-risk equipment; UPS battery backup for data protection.
- **Creative and Applied Design:** Ventilation for adhesives and spray materials, blade safety protocols for physical modelling, proper lighting standards.

WorkSafeBC guidelines are satisfied through mandatory safety orientation and dual-supervisor coverage during high-risk equipment operation. **Technical feasibility is confirmed.**

### 6.2 Updated Cost Analysis - 2026 Adjustment

An independent analysis of Langford, British Columbia's 2026 economic conditions necessitates an adjustment of the original March 2026 startup estimates. Inflationary pressures in the West Shore commercial real estate market and provincial wage adjustments require a recalibration of initial assumptions.

**Cost Adjustments and Identifications:**

**Underestimated Costs:** Initial personnel costs ($110,000 for 2 FTEs + Admin) were sub-market for 2026. Retaining qualified, safety-certified technical instructors in BC requires competitive compensation (estimated $65,000/year per Lead Instructor) plus a 15-20% load for mandatory benefits (WorkSafeBC premiums, CPP, EI). Furthermore, commercial lease estimates must be adjusted to $28-$30/sqft gross to accurately reflect recent municipal property tax impacts on Triple Net (NNN) leases.

**Overestimated Costs:** The initial $10,000-$20,000 marketing budget can be reduced. Organic community demand and strategic partnerships with local school districts will yield high initial conversion rates with a leaner digital marketing spend.

**Missing Cost Categories:** The original budget omitted an equipment depreciation/sinking fund and explicit accounting for commercial general liability (CGL) insurance riders specific to public-access high-risk machinery.

**Table 1: 2026 Market Cost Adjustment Matrix (Startup & Year 1)**

| Category | Initial Estimate (Lean) | 2026 Adjusted Reality (Lean) | Variance |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| Facility Operations (Lease + Utilities) | $96,000 | $120,000 | +25.0% |
| Personnel (Wages + Mandatory Benefits) | $110,000 | $165,000 | +50.0% |
| Equipment, Tooling, & Shipping | $60,000 | $68,000 | +13.3% |
| Legal, Permits, & High-Risk Insurance | $20,000 | $28,000 | +40.0% |
| Marketing & Outreach | $10,000 | $6,000 | -40.0% |
| Development Labor | $17,000 | $17,000 | 0.0% |
| Equipment Sinking Fund (New) | $0 | $10,000 | N/A |
| Contingency (15% of Subtotal) | $46,950 | $62,100 | +32.2% |
| **Total Year 1 Capital Required** | **$359,950** | **$476,100** | **+32.2%** |

### 6.3 Revised Economic Feasibility

The revised 2026 cost analysis confirms that the project remains economically viable, but the break-even threshold and revenue targets must be adjusted upward.

**Table 2: Revised Annual Operating Costs (Ongoing)**

| Cost Item | Lean Model (4,000 sqft) | Expanded Model (6,000 sqft) |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| Facility Lease (Gross) & Utilities | $120,000 | $180,000 |
| Personnel (including Benefits) | $165,000 | $230,000 |
| Maintenance & Sinking Fund | $10,000 | $18,000 |
| Insurance, Operations & Legal | $15,000 | $22,000 |
| **Total Annual Operating** | **$310,000** | **$450,000** |

#### 6.3.1 Break-Even Discussion and Revenue Assumptions

Under the adjusted Lean Model, monthly operating expenses average approximately $25,833. To achieve a sustainable surplus for the contingency reserve, monthly revenue must target $29,000.

To meet this, the original membership pricing assumption must shift. The target becomes 200 active members at $60/month ($12,000), supported by $17,000 monthly distributed across workshop fees, corporate training contracts, institutional partnerships, and sustained grant funding. The commitment to capping any single funding source at 30% of total revenue remains intact, ensuring the center is shielded from abrupt grant cancellations.

*Note: The original project proposal (March 11, 2026) projected $34,000 monthly revenue at $50/month with 160 members. The figures above reflect the March 26 updated cost analysis, which adjusted membership pricing to $60/month and the member target to 200 to account for 2026 market conditions.*

#### 6.3.2 Revenue Diversification Model

The following seven-stream revenue model was developed in the original project proposal. While monthly targets have been recalibrated in the updated analysis, the diversification structure remains the core revenue strategy:

**Table 3: Monthly Revenue Streams (Pre-Adjustment Targets from Proposal)**

| Revenue Source | Unit Price | Monthly Target | Monthly Revenue |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| Individual Memberships | $50/month | 160 members | $8,000 |
| Drop-in Day Passes | $15/visit | 200 visits | $3,000 |
| Workshop Fees (avg.) | $40/attendee | 200 attendees | $8,000 |
| Corporate Training | $500/session | 6 sessions | $3,000 |
| Equipment Surcharges | $15/booking | 175 bookings | $2,625 |
| Event and Room Rental | $250/event | 5 events | $1,250 |
| Grants and Sponsorships | - | - | $8,125 |
| **Total Monthly Revenue** | | | **$34,000** |

Under the updated $60/month membership model with 200 members, the membership line increases to $12,000/month. The remaining streams are expected to generate $17,000/month to reach the $29,000 target. Grant and sponsorship funding ($97,500/year) represents approximately 28% of the $348,000 annual revenue target, remaining within the 30% single-source cap.

#### 6.3.3 Sustainability Trajectory

Earned revenue (memberships, workshops, drop-ins, corporate training, surcharges, rentals) is projected to reach 55% of total income by Year 3, reducing grant dependency and strengthening long-term financial sustainability.

#### 6.3.4 Cost Sensitivity Analysis

**Best-Case Scenario:** Equipment donations from institutional partners (e.g., Camosun College CTAC) offset up to $25,000 in capital expenditures; membership caps at 250 users, generating a comfortable monthly surplus.

**Expected Scenario:** Break-even is achieved in Month 8. Operating costs align with the $310,000 annual projection, requiring sustained baseline grant support alongside earned revenue.

**Worst-Case Scenario:** Commercial lease rates spike above $32/sqft or membership stalls below 120 users. The facility must immediately pivot to the Pop-Up Fallback Model to restrict overhead exposure while rebuilding community engagement.

#### 6.3.5 Evaluation KPIs

The following key performance indicators will be tracked to measure operational and financial health:

1. **Engagement Analytics:** Number of active monthly participants and average hours on-site. Year 1 target: 150 unique participants per quarter. Year 3 target: 500 participants per quarter with a 60% return rate.
2. **Employment Pipelines:** Growth of student internship placements and member career transitions into technical roles.
3. **Social Impact Data:** Member surveys tracking self-reported improvements in well-being, skill confidence, and community connectivity.
4. **Institutional Partnerships:** Minimum of 4 annual partnerships with local schools and businesses to sustain programming.

**Economic feasibility is confirmed.**

### 6.4 Social Feasibility

Crossroads operates on a sliding-scale fee structure to ensure equitable access, mitigating the impact of the increased $60 base membership fee. Targeted outreach for low-income and Indigenous youth through partnerships with School Districts 61, 62, and 63 remains a priority.

#### 6.4.1 Clientele Personas

The following personas were developed from community consultation and survey data to guide programming and outreach:

| Persona | Demographics | Primary Needs | Estimated Share |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| Curious Beginners | All ages, no prior technical experience | Low-pressure environment to explore STEM interests | 35% |
| Experienced Makers | Hobbyists and professionals | Industrial-grade tools not available in home workshops; collaborative community | 25% |
| Students and Educators | Post-secondary students; K-12 teachers | Supplementary lab time beyond institutional hours; ADST curriculum resources | 25% |
| Community Builders | Retirees, volunteers | Social connection through mentorship, event organization, and peer support | 15% |

Additional target populations include youth ages 12-18, adult career changers seeking flexible non-traditional schedules, and retirees contributing as volunteer mentors.

#### 6.4.2 Price Sensitivity

The community survey found that 61% of respondents preferred a monthly membership fee in the $25-$50 range. The updated $60/month base fee exceeds this preference band, making the sliding-scale structure essential for maintaining equitable access. The $15 drop-in option provides a lower-commitment entry point for price-sensitive users.

#### 6.4.3 Community Ecosystem

The volunteer mentorship cohort, projected at 15 to 25 active members contributing approximately 200 hours monthly, fosters a peer-support ecosystem. This model anchors the facility as a vital "third place" for community development, blending structured learning with social connectivity.

**Social feasibility remains highly robust.**

### 6.5 Environmental and Cultural Feasibility

#### 6.5.1 Environmental Considerations

Light fabrication waste is managed via standard commercial protocols. Discipline-specific waste management includes:

- **Digital Fabrication:** Dust collection system on CNC router captures particulate matter; 3D printer waste (PLA, PETG) is recyclable through commercial filament recycling programs; laser cutter operates within an enclosed safety enclosure with fume extraction.
- **Robotics and Electronics:** Soldering fume extraction at each station; battery fire-safe storage; electronic component waste managed through BC-certified e-waste recycling.
- **Creative and Applied Design:** Ventilation for adhesives and spray materials; blade waste and physical modelling scrap disposed via standard commercial waste streams.

An emphasis on iterative prototyping inherently minimizes raw material waste, as designs are refined digitally before physical fabrication.

#### 6.5.2 Cultural Alignment

The British Columbia Ministry of Education's Applied Design, Skills, and Technologies (ADST) curriculum emphasizes experiential learning and iterative design across K-12 education. Crossroads directly extends the ADST model into the community setting, bridging the gap between secondary education and professional practice. The facility addresses the infrastructure deficit caused by rapid municipal expansion in the West Shore, where population growth (3.95% year-over-year) has outpaced the development of community learning infrastructure.

**Environmental and cultural feasibility is confirmed.**

### 6.6 Political and Legal Feasibility

#### 6.6.1 Regulatory Roadmap

The following legal and regulatory requirements must be satisfied prior to launch:

1. **BC Societies Act:** Incorporation as a nonprofit society to maximize public trust and grant eligibility. Nonprofit bylaws are a deliverable of the Detailed Design phase (pre-launch student labor, Table 1).
2. **WorkSafeBC Compliance:** Safety orientation protocols, dual-supervisor coverage during high-risk operations, and premium payments for workshop environments.
3. **Commercial General Liability (CGL) Insurance:** Specialized riders necessary for an open-access facility housing CO2 lasers, CNC mills, and soldering stations. The updated Lean Model budget allocates $28,000 for legal, permits, and high-risk insurance (up from $20,000 in the original proposal).
4. **Accessible Canada Act:** Full facility compliance for accessibility.

#### 6.6.2 Institutional Partnerships

Political support for workforce readiness programs in the West Shore is strong. Key institutional partnerships include:

- **Camosun College CTAC (Technology Access Centre):** Preliminary discussions for student placements and limited equipment transfers, projected to offset $15,000-$30,000 in startup costs.
- **VIATEC (Victoria Innovation, Advanced Technology, and Entrepreneurship Council):** Access to over 900 potential corporate sponsors and mentors for programming and funding support.
- **School Districts 61, 62, and 63:** Targeted outreach partnerships for youth programming, free trial workshops, and ADST curriculum alignment.

**Political and legal feasibility is confirmed.**

### 6.7 Operational Feasibility

#### 6.7.1 Staffing Model

The operational model is built on a four-tier staffing structure:

- **Executive Director (1 FTE):** Cameron Kibble. Leads strategic development, partnership outreach, and day-to-day facility management.
- **Lab Supervisors (2 FTE, salaried):** Manage equipment operations via staggered shifts covering 63 staffed hours per week, with dual-operator supervision during peak afternoon and weekend hours. Compensation is budgeted at $65,000/year per Lead Instructor plus 15-20% mandatory benefits (WorkSafeBC premiums, CPP, EI).
- **Board of Directors:** Volunteer board of 5 professionals providing governance and legal compliance oversight.
- **Volunteer Mentors:** 15-25 active members drawn from local professionals and senior students, contributing approximately 200 hours monthly in peer-to-peer technical support. A "train the trainer" model is employed to reduce additional paid staffing requirements over time.

#### 6.7.2 Weekly Operating Schedule

The facility operates 73 total hours per week across two access tiers:

| Day | Staffed Hours | Self-Access Hours | Total |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| Monday - Friday | 10:00 AM - 8:00 PM (10 hrs x 5 = 50 hrs) | 8:00 PM - 10:00 PM (2 hrs x 5 = 10 hrs) | 60 hrs |
| Saturday | 10:00 AM - 6:00 PM (8 hrs) | - | 8 hrs |
| Sunday | 12:00 PM - 5:00 PM (5 hrs) | - | 5 hrs |
| **Weekly Total** | **63 hours** | **10 hours** | **73 hours** |

Self-access hours (weekday evenings 8:00-10:00 PM) are restricted to member card access in low-risk zones only. High-risk equipment (laser cutter, CNC router) requires staffed supervision.

This schedule directly addresses survey findings: 68% of respondents preferred weekday evening access and 59% preferred weekend availability.

A mandatory safety orientation protocol complies with provincial health and safety mandates. **Operational feasibility is confirmed.**

### 6.8 Schedule Feasibility

A 12-month phased implementation timeline is maintained across five phases:

#### Phase 1: Foundation (Months 1-3)
- Nonprofit incorporation under BC Societies Act
- Lease negotiation and facility selection
- Board of Directors recruitment
- Initial grant applications submitted

#### Phase 2: Build-Out (Months 4-6)
- Facility renovation (electrical, ventilation, accessibility)
- Equipment procurement and commissioning
- Safety protocol development and WorkSafeBC compliance
- Staff hiring and training

#### Phase 3: Soft Launch (Months 7-9)
- Pilot workshops with limited enrollment
- Safety orientation protocol testing
- Community feedback collection
- Partnership formalization with School Districts 61, 62, and 63

#### Phase 4: Full Launch (Months 10-12)
- Full public launch at 73 hours/week
- All four discipline areas operational
- Membership enrollment drive
- Comprehensive evaluation against KPIs

#### Phase 5: Optimization (Ongoing)
- Revenue diversification monitoring
- Programming adjustments based on engagement analytics
- Scale assessment for Alternative B transition

**Parallel Execution:** Phases 1 and 2 have natural dependencies (lease must precede renovation), but grant applications, staff recruitment, and board development can proceed in parallel with facility selection.

#### 6.8.1 Risk Triggers and Contingencies

| Risk | Trigger | Contingency |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| Facility Delay | Facility partnership not secured within first 3 months | Adopt pop-up model, renting community center space for mobile workshops |
| Funding Shortfall | Grant funding lower than projected | Scale to lean budget of $476,100 (adjusted); prioritize high-demand disciplines (3D printing at 72%, software at 58%) |
| Low Participation | Attendance targets not met by Month 10 | Reallocate marketing budget toward free trial workshops and direct partnerships with School Districts 61, 62, and 63 |

**Schedule feasibility is confirmed.**

